problem_prompt: You are an expert in number theory. Solve the following problem. The number $2^{1993}+3^{1993}$ is a multiple of $5.$ What is the units digit of the quotient $\frac{2^{1993}+3^{1993}}{5}?$
solution:
We want to find the units digit of the quotient \[\frac{2^{1993}+3^{1993}}5.\]We list the final two digits of  $2^n$ and $3^n$ in the next table. We also compute the units digit of the quotient whenever $2^n+3^n$ is divisible by $5.$

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|}

\end{tabular}We notice that after the first pair, the sequence repeats every $20.$ Therefore \[{2^{1993}+3^{1993}}\equiv {2^{13}+3^{13}}\equiv15\pmod{100}.\]So, the units digit of the quotient $\frac{2^{1993}+3^{1993}}5$ is $\boxed{3}.$

(Note: "mod 100" essentially means "remainder when the number is divided by 100".  So, $2^{1993} + 3^{1993} \equiv 15 \pmod{100}$ means that $2^{1993} + 3^{1993}$ is 15 more than a multiple of 100.)
gpt_response:
To tackle this problem, we first look at the powers of $2$ and $3$ modulo $5$:

$2^1 \equiv 2 \pmod{5}$
$2^2 \equiv 4 \pmod{5}$
$2^3 \equiv 3 \pmod{5}$
$2^4 \equiv 1 \pmod{5}$
$2^5 \equiv 2 \pmod{5}$

and

$3^1 \equiv 3 \pmod{5}$
$3^2 \equiv 4 \pmod{5}$
$3^3 \equiv 2 \pmod{5}$
$3^4 \equiv 1 \pmod{5}$
$3^5 \equiv 3 \pmod{5}$

Since $2^{4} \equiv 1 \pmod{5}$ and $3^{4} \equiv 1 \pmod{5}$, we have:

$2^{1993} \equiv 2^{(1992+1)} \equiv (2^4)^{498} \cdot 2 \equiv 1^{498} \cdot 2 \equiv 2 \pmod{5}$

and

$3^{1993} \equiv 3^{(1992+1)} \equiv (3^4)^{498} \cdot 3 \equiv 1^{498} \cdot 3 \equiv 3 \pmod{5}$

Hence, $2^{1993}+3^{1993} \equiv 2 + 3 \equiv 5 \equiv 0 \pmod{5}.$

So, $\frac{2^{1993}+3^{1993}}{5}$ is an integer. The units digit of a multiple of $10$ is always $\boxed{0}$.
